<h1>LEASING INFORMATION</h1><div class="whitebox">Each player has the option to lease <i>out</i> their horses to let other players train and/or race them. They can also take <i>in </i>leases to train and/or race other people's horses. A player must have a Trainer hired to accept leases, because the Trainer determines a player's leasing limits (LL). 

Additionally, if a player hopes to race a leased horse, they must have a Trainer <i><u>and</u></i> Jockey hired.&nbsp;Unlike Training and Racing Limits, Leasing Limits can not increase through PR Bonuses. Your Leasing Limit depends entirely on which trainer you have hired at the moment in time.</div><div class="purplebox"><h3>IMPORTANT : Regarding Leasing Another Player's Horse to Race</h3>It is important to note that the <u>owner</u> of the horse gets the purse from winning races! Additionally, Wallets are not allowed in leases as it is not attached to the horse, but the player. Please keep this in mind when&nbsp;negotiating leases.</div><div align="center"><small><a href="https://sta.sh/01x1msyutfnh#top">Back to Top</a></small></div>

</div>
<h1>PR BONUSES</h1><div class="mods-hh split-65"><div class="mods-column-ll"><div class="whitebox">Each time a player is awarded a PR Bonus, they <b>permanently receive +5 additional trainings and races per week.</b> This bonus adds on to the limit set by the player's hired Trainer and Jockey, <i>which are still required to make requests.</i> To earn this bonus, a player must get their horse to 100 PR by racing them successfully (see the teal box). A player can earn a maximum of 10 PR bonuses total, with bonuses only given once per horse.

For example, a player with a Rookie Trainer and Rookie Jockey would have 20 Training and 20 Races each week <i>normally</i>. But if that player were to have 10 horses with at least 100 PR, then that player would enjoy a total of 70 Training and 70 Races each week!

</div></div><div class="mods-column-rr"><div class="tealbox"><h3>Earning PR</h3>When a horse does well in races, it will earn PR depending on its placement.

<div align="center"><b>1st Place</b> = 15 PR</div><div align="center"><b>2nd place</b> = 7 PR</div><div align="center"><b>3rd Place</b> = 3 PR</div><div align="center"><b>4th / 5th Place</b> = 1 PR</div><div align="center">Everything Else = 0 PR</div></div></div></div><div align="center"><small><a href="https://sta.sh/01x1msyutfnh#top">Back to Top</a></small></div>

<h1>STALL INFORMATION</h1><div class="whitebox" align="left">In order to house more horses -- whether they are obtained through buying customs, from a player, or breeding two horses to create a foal -- you must first have space in your stable! <b>There are two types of stalls</b>; Adults and Maternal.&nbsp;You can view the stalls you own and the ones available for purchase (along with their prices) in the Vault. When you begin playing Turfside, you receive one free Adult stall to fill with your first horse!</div><div class="left"><div class="purplebox"><h3>Adult Stalls</h3>These stalls are for your Adult horses. Each player can have a maximum of 15 adult stalls, which means a player can have a maximum of 15 horses in their stables at any given time.

In order to expand your Stable to house more horses, you must purchase additional Adult Stalls. A player can unlock and purchase as many Adult Stalls they wish at any given time, as long as they have the Coins to do so. 

In "The Vault", stalls that are available for a player to purchase will have its price written in grey ink. Stalls that are owned by a player, but are unoccupied, will be labeled as "Available" with bolded black ink. Finally, stalls that are occupied by a horse will have that horse's ID# in bolded red ink and pink BG.
</div></div><div class="right"><div class="purplebox"><h3>Maternity Stalls</h3>Maternal Stalls are specially made to house foals and yearlings. A stable must have at least one Maternal Stall available in order to breed their mares, although you can still stud your stallions out to other stables that have a Maternal Stall unlocked.

When a foal is born at your stables, it will live in the Maternal Stall until it ages to Adulthood. At that point, it will be automatically moved into an available Adult stall. <b>If there is no space</b>, you will receive a notice that you have two weeks to correct the issue by making space or selling the foal.

After two weeks and the issue hasn't been corrected, you will be given a second warning and an additional one week. If the problem is still not fixed at this time, your stable will be frozen and unable to participate in Turfside until the issue is resolved.
</div></div>
